## Recommended: Use `System.IO.Abstractions`

For `File.ReadAllText`, `File.WriteAllText`, and `Directory.Exists`, the best approach is the established **System.IO.Abstractions** NuGet package — no need to write custom wrappers.

### 1. Install the package

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes

```csharp
public class MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Read(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Write(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool DirectoryExists(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```bash
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});
// Pre-create the directory so Directory.Exists returns true
mockFs.AddDirectory("/data");

var sut = new MyService(mockFs);

Assert.True(sut.DirectoryExists("/data"));
Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", sut.Read("/data/config.json"));
```

---

**Why this over a custom wrapper?** `System.IO.Abstractions` is battle-tested, covers the full `System.IO` surface, and ships a ready-made `MockFileSystem` — no hand-rolled mocks needed.

Once installed, you can use the `migrate-static-to-wrapper` skill to bulk-replace existing `File.*`/`Directory.*` call sites with the injected `IFileSystem` equivalent.
